  "texts": [
    "Therefore, the real-space superlattice is similarly rotated and expanded by 1/(2 sin(θ/2)).",
    "By taking the inverse Fourier transform, we can interpret the continuum model as Dirac fermions on two layers with an interlayer hopping that is local 75 and spatially modulated with wavevector ∼ k θ.How did a periodic Hamiltonian emerge from generically incommensurate twist angles?",
    "Due to the intralayer kinetic penalty, we imagined restricting to plane wave momenta p near K. However, an electron with starting momentum p in principle may scatter to p + ∆p that is far from K through multiple interlayer tunneling processes that change the momentum by integer multiples of b j.",
    "In particular, if through this multistep scattering process, it ends up on layer l and gains momentum ∆p = j n j b j ≃ G l G that is close to a monolayer RLV, it can undergo 'Bragg scattering' by -G l G to return near K. The incommensurability manifests in the fact that G l G is not expressible as an integer sum of moiré RLVs for general twist angles.",
    "However, such effects are exponentially suppressed at small θ due the high order of perturbation theory required."
  ],
